  "prompt": "When and how did WWI start and end?",
  "response": "World War I, also known as the Great War, was a global conflict that primarily took place in Europe from 1914 to 1918. Here's an overview of when and how it started and ended:\n\n### **Start of World War I**\n\n**Date:**  \n- **July 28, 1914**\n\n**Causes and Events Leading to the Outbreak:**\n\n1. **Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand:**  \n   - On **June 28, 1914**, Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria-Hungary and his wife, Sophie, were assassinated in Sarajevo by **Gavrilo Princip**, a Bosnian Serb nationalist associated with the group **Black Hand**. This event is widely regarded as the immediate catalyst for the war.\n\n2. **July Crisis:**  \n   - The assassination triggered a series of diplomatic and military escalations among the major European powers, known as the **July Crisis**. Austria-Hungary, with the backing of Germany (often referred to as the **Blank Check Assurance**), issued an ultimatum to Serbia, where the assassin had connections.\n\n3. **Declarations of War:**  \n   - Serbia's partial compliance led Austria-Hungary to declare war on **July 28, 1914**. \n   - Due to a complex web of alliances:\n     - **Russia** mobilized in defense of Serbia.\n     - **Germany** declared war on Russia on **August 1, 1914**, and on **France** on **August 3, 1914**.\n     - **Germany**'s invasion of Belgium to reach France prompted Britain to declare war on Germany on **August 4, 1914**.\n   - These declarations transformed a regional conflict into a full-scale world war involving multiple nations across different continents.\n\n### **End of World War I**\n\n**Armistice Date:**  \n- **November 11, 1918**\n\n**Peace Treaty:**  \n- **Treaty of Versailles** signed on **June 28, 1919**\n\n**How the War Ended:**\n\n1. **Military Stalemate and Exhaustion:**  \n   - By 1917-1918, the war had reached a brutal stalemate on the Western Front, leading to immense casualties and economic strain for all involved nations.\n\n2. **Entry of the United States:**  \n   - In **April 1917**, the United States entered the war on the side of the Allies, providing fresh troops and resources that bolstered the Allied forces.\n\n3. **Collapse of the Central Powers:**  \n   - Internal dissent, economic hardship, and military defeats led to the collapse of the Central Powers:\n     - **Ottoman Empire** signed an armistice on **October 30, 1918**.\n     - **Austria-Hungary** faced internal revolutions and signed an armistice on **November 3, 1918**.\n     - **Bulgaria** signed an armistice on **September 29, 1918**.\n\n4. **German Armistice:**  \n   - Facing imminent invasion and internal revolution, **Germany** agreed to an armistice on **November 11, 1918**, effectively ending the fighting.\n\n5. **Peace Negotiations:**  \n   - The **Paris Peace Conference** convened in 1919, leading to the **Treaty of Versailles**, which officially ended the war. The treaty imposed significant territorial losses, military restrictions, and reparations on Germany, reshaping the geopolitical landscape of Europe.\n\n### **Aftermath**\n\nWorld War I had profound and lasting impacts, including:\n\n- Redrawing of national boundaries, leading to the creation of new nations like Czechoslovakia and Yugoslavia.\n- Significant loss of life and widespread destruction.\n- Social and political upheaval, contributing to the conditions that eventually led to World War II.\n- The League of Nations was established in an attempt to prevent future conflicts, though it ultimately proved ineffective in stopping aggression by Axis powers in the subsequent decade.\n\nWorld War I fundamentally altered the course of the 20th century, setting the stage for major political, social, and technological changes worldwide.",
